         <lg>
            <head type="main-authorial">HALCYON DAYS.<note type="editorial" resp="wwa" place="end" xml:id="n1">Reprinted in the "Sands
               at Seventy Annex" to <hi rend="italic">Leaves of Grass</hi> (1888).</note></head>
            <l>Not from successful love alone,</l>
            <l>Nor wealth, nor honored middle age, nor <choice>
                  <orig>vic- <lb/> tories</orig>
                  <reg>victories</reg>
               </choice> of politics or war.</l>
            <l>But as life wanes, and all the turbulent passions <lb/> calm,</l>
            <l>As gorgeous, vapory, silent hues cover the <choice>
                  <orig>even- <lb/> ing</orig>
                  <reg>evening</reg>
               </choice> sky,</l>
            <l>As softness, fulness, rest, suffuse the spirit and <lb/> frame like freshier,
               balmier air;</l>
            <l>As the days take on a mellower light, and the <lb/> apple at last hangs really
               finished and <choice>
                  <orig> in- <lb/> dolent </orig>
                  <reg>indolent</reg>
               </choice> ripe on the tree,</l>
            <l>Then for the teeming quietest, happiest days of <lb/> all!</l>
            <l>The brooding and blissful halcyon days!<note type="editorial" resp="wwa"
               xml:id="n2" place="end">In December 1887, another poet's "Halcyon Days" appeared in the <hi
                  rend="italic">New York Herald</hi>, though Whitman's poem and this earlier one
               have little but their title in common. When Whitman revised the poem for inclusion
               in "Sands at Seventy," he omitted the words "spirit and" in the fifth line.</note></l>
            <closer>
               <signed rend="right">â€” <hi rend="italic">Walt Whitman</hi>.</signed>
            </closer>
         </lg>
      </body>
